'''Shimosuwa Aozuka Kofun''' (下諏訪青塚古墳) is a [[:en:Kofun|Kofun]] (ancient Kofun) located in [[:en:Shimosuwa|Shimosuwa, Nagano]], [[:en:Nagano Prefecture|Nagano Prefecture]], Japan. Its type is that of a [[:en:Zenpokoenfun|Zenpokoenfun]], and it is Historic Site1 as a historic site by Nagano Prefecture.

== Overview ==
The Kofun was constructed on the tip of a hill projecting westward in the northern region of [[:en:Lake Suwa|Lake Suwa]]. It is situated near the {{ill|Shimosha Akimiya|ja|諏訪大社下社秋宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimosha Akimiya|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} of [[:en:Suwa-taisha|Suwa Taisha]]. The site is within the shrine's property, and parts of the mound (especially the eastern side) have been eroded by surrounding developments. The {{ill|Aozuka Shrine|ja|青塚社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aozuka Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, a subsidiary shrine of Suwa Taisha, is located in the western constriction area of the mound.

The kofun is keyhole-shaped with its front part oriented to the north-northwest. It is the only keyhole-shaped Kofun in the Suwa region and belongs to the late phase of this style. {{ill|Cylindrical haniwa|ja|円筒埴輪|1=Cylindrical Haniwa|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cylindrical haniwa|13=User:Immanuelle/Cylindrical Haniwa|qq=}} have been discovered on the mound's surface, making it the only example in the Suwa region where haniwa have been found. Historical records from the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]] mention the discovery of human-shaped haniwa, which were later reburied, though recent investigations have found no items other than cylindrical haniwa. 

The burial facility is a {{ill|horizontal stone chamber|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/horizontal stone chamber|13=User:Immanuelle/Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=}} exposed and open on the western constriction area of the rear mound, approximately five meters above the base level. The chamber is constructed with natural [[:en:Andesite|andesite]] stones in a random stone masonry style. It measures 5.5 meters in total length. Although the corridor leading to the chamber has been destroyed, it is presumed to have been a double-chambered type. Few burial goods from the chamber are known.

The Aozuka Kofun is estimated to have been constructed in the late 6th century. Scholars suggest links to the {{ill|Kanasa clan|ja|金刺氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanasa clan|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 金刺部氏}}, the ritualist family of Suwa Taisha's Shimosha, and connections with other keyhole-shaped Kofuns distributed along the [[:en:Tenryū River|Tenryu River]]. This makes the mound an important archaeological site for studying the political landscape of ancient Suwa.

The Kofun was Historic Site1 as a Nagano Prefecture historic site in 1965.

== Mound ==
The mound's area are as follows:
* Mound length: 57 meters
* Rear part:
''' Diameter: 34 meters (estimated reconstruction)
''' Height: 8.1 meters
* Front part:
''' Width: 40 meters (estimated reconstruction)
''' Height: 8 meters

According to the site's intypeation board, the primary axis length is 67 meters, the rear part's diameter is 33.4 meters, and the front part's width is 42.8 meters.

<gallery>
File:Shimosuwa Aozuka Kofun Aozuka-sha and sekishitsu.JPG|Constriction area with Aozuka Shrine (left) and stone chamber (top right)
File:Shimosuwa Aozuka Kofun sekishitsu.JPG|Entrance to the stone chamber
</gallery>

== Historic Site ==
=== Nagano Prefecture-Designated Historic Site ===
* Historic Site:
''' Shimosuwa Aozuka Kofun - Designated on February 25, 1965.

